    <h3 style="color:#326867;font-size: 26px;font-weight: bold;">
      Depression: The Hidden Illness <br/>
    </h3>
    <p>
      <STRONG>RALEIGH, N.C. - Jul. 7, 2018 </STRONG> <br>
    <p style="line-height: 175%">
      It's a Friday morning, the weekend is hours within reach, and your alarm goes off. As you proceed through your morning routine while grabbing a breakfast bar to head out the door to work or class, you feel a weight on your chest.
      Your brain may feel as though it's on auto-pilot and your body is acting on muscle memory. When you walk into class, there is chatter and excitement about the events taking place later that evening or the music festival that's in town over the weekend. But you don't feel excited. Despite it being Friday, this feels like just another morning in a long stretch of endless days that you are pushing through. <br>
      <br>
      Here's the thing - mental illness often masks itself. Depression will fight to stay hidden until someone decides to yank it out and take hold of it.
      While many people try to navigate the ups and downs of life, some people have significantly more bad days than they do good days. There is a difference between having a bad week due to various events in one's life and having consistently bad days or weeks, even with a few good days in between. <br>
    </p>
    <h4>Could I have depression?</h4>
    <p style="line-height: 175%">
      While everyone has different personalities and circumstances, there are a few telltale signs that may indicate that you could be suffering from depression rather than just having an off-week. As you read through the following list, take an honest look at your answers. Do you relate to any of these signs?
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>You no longer get excited about activities you used to enjoy or you have stopped participating in those activities all together</li>
      <li>Your sleeping patterns have changed- you either have a hard time falling asleep or you sleep a lot more than you used to</li>
      <li>Even if you got plenty of sleep, you feel drained throughout the following day</li>
      <li>You feel as though your days are blending together and there is nothing to look forward to</li>
      <li>You no longer want to make decisions or put too much thought into things</li>
      <li>You get irritated or annoyed by simple things, such as someone asking you a question</li>
      <li>When you're at home, you lay in bed even when you're not ready to sleep</li>
      <li>While you used to eat on a relatively normal schedule, you now eat significantly more than you used to, or you have a hard time even eating at all</li>
      <li>You have suicidal thoughts beyond just thinking about the topic- you may wonder what the least painful method is, even if you believe you have no intention on acting upon it</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="line-height: 175%">
      Did any of those sentences hit home for you? If so, you are not alone. Remember the scenario introduced at the beginning of this article, where everyone else in the classroom appeared to be excited about the weekend? What if I told you that out of the 100 people in that classroom, that seven others might have also been feeling the same way you were? According to the Anxiety and Depression Association of America, 6.7% of the U.S. population over the age of 18 has been diagnosed with depression.
      Keep in mind, that statistic includes those that have been formally diagnosed by a doctor- there are many others suffering in silence.
    </p>

