    <h4>How to help yourself</h4>
    <p style="line-height: 175%">
      There is no other 'you' in this world. You are your own person and you have different interests, a different living situation, and different relationships than anyone else you may know.
      While there is no 'one size fits all' path to battling depression, take comfort in the fact that many have come before you with this diagnosis. <br>
      A good starting point to begin the process of dealing with your depression is accepting that you are suffering from a mental illness. You need to admit to yourself that something is off.
      By admitting this to yourself, you do not have to feel good about it. Maybe it will feel like part of the weight is lifted off of your chest, but maybe it will make you feel worse.
      Nobody likes to admit they are suffering, but if you want change to happen you will need to make an intentional effort. <br>
      After you have owned your mental illness, there is a variety of routes you can take to healing. You need to figure out what works best for you.
    </p>
    <b> Here are some ideas: </b>
    <ul>
      <li>Exercise. If you don't have the motivation to get up and go to the gym, go for a walk around your neighborhood </li>
      <li>Start a journal and write down your thoughts </li>
      <li>Try to make it to events or hangouts with your friends, even if it's only once per week </li>
      <li>Speak to a close and trusted friend or family member about the feelings you've been having </li>
      <li>Consider seeing a psychologist- there is no commitment in going, but a professional can help you dissect your feelings and provide tips catered to your needs in overcoming your depression. A psychologist may also be able to recognize the need for medication to assist you in your healing </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>
      How to help a loved one
    </h4>
    <p style="line-height: 175%">
      If you notice changes in a friend or family member and think they may have depression, you will need to tread slowly. This person may not even realize they have depression.
      Invite them to grab coffee and spend time with them or send them a message asking how they are doing. Show them that you care.
      If someone has confided in you and told you that they are battling depression, it is important that you recognize the level of trust they have in you.
      Be a friend, but do not be a helicopter. Depending on the severity, they may need guidance and an extra push to assist them in their healing. Remember, you are there to support them and not to heal them. That person will need to heal themselves.
    </p>

